Sudden Network Slowdowns

Microsoft Defender for Endpoint Threat Hunt Portfolio Project

Project Overview

This project documents a threat hunt investigation involving sudden network slowdowns within an internal 10.0.0.0/16 network.

The server team observed significant network performance degradation on older devices. After external DDoS activity was ruled out, the investigation focused on whether suspicious internal activity was causing the slowdown.

The hunt used Microsoft Defender for Endpoint telemetry and KQL queries to identify excessive failed network connections, investigate possible port scanning, review suspicious process execution, and determine the response actions needed to contain the affected device.

This investigation used Microsoft Defender for Endpoint telemetry and KQL queries to review:

- Failed internal network connections
- Suspicious local IP activity
- Sequential connection behavior
- Possible internal port scanning
- PowerShell execution
- Suspicious script activity
- Administrative account usage
- MITRE ATT&CK technique mapping
- Remediation and response steps

Scenario Summary

The server team noticed network performance degradation on older devices connected to the internal 10.0.0.0/16 network.

After external DDoS attacks were ruled out, the security team suspected that something inside the network may have been causing the issue.

The environment allowed internal traffic by default, and PowerShell usage was unrestricted. This created a risk that a device inside the network could run scripts, download large files, or perform port scanning against other internal hosts.

The investigation focused on identifying whether excessive failed connections were occurring and whether those connections were tied to suspicious process activity.

