Final Conclusion

This threat hunt confirmed that the sudden network slowdowns were associated with suspicious internal port scanning activity.

The investigation identified repeated failed network connections from `vme-windows-hun`, with local IP `10.1.0.118` showing the highest failed connection count.

Further analysis showed that the failed connections followed a pattern consistent with port scanning. A pivot into process telemetry confirmed that a PowerShell script named `portscan.ps1` launched around the same time.

The script was executed through PowerShell using execution policy bypass and was associated with the `dhacker` account. This was not expected behavior and was not approved by the administrator.

The device was isolated, a malware scan was performed, and no malware was found. Because the activity was still suspicious, the device remained isolated and a ticket was created to have it reimaged or rebuilt.

This project demonstrates how failed network connection patterns, process execution telemetry, and account context can be combined to investigate internal network slowdowns and identify suspicious discovery activity.
